recommandationVideos.Description:
In which John Green teaches you the history of Islam, including the revelation of the Qu'ran to Muhammad, the five pillars of Islam, how the Islamic empire got its start, the Rightly Guided Caliphs, and more. Learn about hadiths, Abu Bakr, and whether the Umma has anything to do with Uma Thurman (spoiler alert: it doesn't). Also, learn a little about the split between Sunni and Shia Muslims, and how to tell if this year's Ramadan is going to be difficult for your Muslim friends. Let's try to keep the flame wars out of this reasoned discussion.

What is Ramadan:

‚ñ™Ô∏è Fasting was ordained by God before Islam, for followers of Jesus and Moses
‚ñ™Ô∏è Ramadan was the month in which Qur‚Äôan was first revealed
‚ñ™Ô∏è It begins on new moon Crescent of the 9th month 
‚ñ™Ô∏è Ramadan begins when sun goes down and the new moon arrives
‚ñ™Ô∏è From dawn we fast, until sun goes down below the horizon
‚ñ™Ô∏è No eating or drinking when its daylight 
‚ñ™Ô∏è Watch what you say and do, be kind and charitable
‚ñ™Ô∏è If you are ill or too old or on a journey you don‚Äôt have to fast
‚ñ™Ô∏è Children under 14 don‚Äôt need to fast, but some start earlier
‚ñ™Ô∏è It lasts for the whole moon month of Ramadan 
‚ñ™Ô∏è Many Muslims go to the mosque for the night prayer (‚ÄòEisha)
‚ñ™Ô∏è After ‚ÄôEisha prayers, the Qur‚Äôan is recited by the Imam through the nights of Ramadan
‚ñ™Ô∏è The last ten days are special, because that‚Äôs when the Qur‚Äôan was first revealed
‚ñ™Ô∏è Some people stay alone trying to get closer to God for the last ten days (I‚Äôtikaf)
‚ñ™Ô∏è Ramadan is 30 days, sometimes 29, depending on the next moon sighting
‚ñ™Ô∏è When the new moon of Shawwal (10th month) arrives it is Eid!
‚ñ™Ô∏è Eid means the Happy Returns! 
‚ñ™Ô∏è It‚Äôs a day when everybody realises Ramadan has gone, and feel sad‚Ä¶until it comes again!

John Green teaches you about the so-called Dark Ages, which it turns out weren't as uniformly dark as you may have been led to believe. recommandationVideos.Title: Islam‚Äôs Origins: Myth and Material Evidence
recommandationVideos.Description: The traditional narrative of Islam‚Äôs origins centers on the career of the prophet Muhammad (d. 632 CE) in Arabia and the rapid spread of his movement throughout the Near East immediately after his death. Over the past half-century, however, scholars have come to realize that this picture is the product of the Islamic community of the eighth, ninth, and later centuries and that its goal of providing a satisfying narrative may not accurately reflect how Islam actually began and grew into the major world religion we know today. In this lecture, Fred M. Donner argues that a more historically accurate view of Islam‚Äôs origins has been hindered by the scarcity of documentary evidence from the seventh century and considers some of the key sources that may help us understand these momentous events in Islamic history.

Does the Quran prophesy the end of the state of Israel? There's been a lot of social media commentary on this subject, and Dr. Shabir Ally weighs in. He says that chapter 17 in the Quran is thought to be a commentary on current affairs. He says this modern interpretation comes from a place of desperation and a desire to find hope in the Quran. However, he argues that the verses in question were futuristic from the time God told the Israelites it would happen, but not futuristic in our time. Dr. Shabir doesn't like this modern interpretation for another reason: it likens contemporary Muslims to those who originally destroyed the temple in 586 BC. He says we can draw an indirect lesson from this verse: all human beings need to be aware that if they misuse the power God gives them, God can diminish them in this life.

recommandationVideos.Description:
In a classic research-based TEDx Talk, Dr. Lara Boyd describes how neuroplasticity gives you the power to shape the brain you want. Recorded at TEDxVancouver at Rogers Arena on November 14, 2015.

YouTube Tags: brain science, brain, stroke, neuroplasticity, science, motor learning, identity, TED, TEDxVancouver, TEDxVancouver 2015, Vancouver, TEDx, Rogers Arena, Vancouver speakers, Vancouver conference, ideas worth spreading, great idea,

Our knowledge of the brain is evolving at a breathtaking pace, and Dr. Lara Boyd is positioned at the cutting edge of these discoveries. In 2006, she was recruited by the University of British Columbia to become the Canada Research Chair in Neurobiology and Motor Learning. Since that time she has established the Brain Behaviour Lab, recruited and trained over 40 graduate students, published more than 80 papers and been awarded over $5 million in funding. 

Dr. Boyd‚Äôs efforts are leading to the development of novel, and more effective, therapeutics for individuals with brain damage, but they are also shedding light on broader applications. By learning new concepts, taking advantage of opportunities, and participating in new activities, you are physically changing who you are, and opening up a world of endless possibility.

Hey everyone!  This video continues the series on the Summary of Genesis by analyzing its second chapter, which tells a more detailed story of how God created Man and Woman.

This chapter gives us great insight into God's ordination of marital roles in accordance with the Scriptures. Please understand that this video is NOT saying Man is superior to Woman in any way. However, it is important to recognize that God did have a specific role in mind for both genders in marriage. Also, please understand that these roles are meant to be primary in nature, but this does NOT mean that the opposite gender is not allowed to perform duties that are meant to be for the other. (For example, God ordained the wife to support her husband, but this does not mean that a husband should not support his wife).

Thanks for watching this video, and make sure to hit the "like" and "subscribe" buttons for more videos on God's Word! Also, please make sure to share this video with others!  You never know who might need to see it!  Thanks a lot and God Bless!  :)

üè¢ Hard Beginnings in Garthamlock:
Born and raised in the East End of Glasgow, specifically in the tough neighborhood of Garthamlock, Joe reflects on the challenges of his upbringing that shaped his journey.


ü§Ø Impact on Mental Health:
Joe shares the untold story of the toll the 'Ice Cream Wars' took on his mental health. The lasting effects of this traumatic experience are laid bare as he discusses the emotional scars left behind.


‚ù§Ô∏è Empathy and Compassion:
In a powerful segment, Joe speaks about the importance of empathy and compassion for the victim's family. Despite being wronged, he emphasizes understanding the pain of others affected by the events.


üåü Positive Message to the Younger Generation:
Turning adversity into wisdom, Joe delivers a positive message to the younger generation. He addresses the negativity of crime and encourages a path of resilience, growth, and compassion.


üë®‚Äçüë©‚Äçüëß‚Äçüë¶ Family Support:

Join us in this deeply moving episode of The Muslimi Experience  Podcast where Abdirahman Warsame, our guest, shares his powerful story of resilience and transformation.
Starting from his first encounter with death at just five years old, Abdirahman takes us through the pivotal moments of his life that shaped his understanding of the world. Witnessing a tragic incident in his early years, he recounts how his perspective on life and death was profoundly impacted from a young age.

Throughout his high school years, Abdirahman faced inner conflicts and judgments, leading him to a crucial point of self-realization. His story of confronting peer pressure, experimenting with substances, and ultimately finding clarity through the wise words of a close friend, highlights the importance of self-awareness and support in our lives.

This episode is not just about the challenges; it's about finding peace, understanding, and the power of friendship. Abdirahman journey to self-discovery is a testament to the strength of the human spirit and the transformative power of introspection and support.

Don't miss this inspirational episode with Abdirahman on The Muslimi Experience Podcast. Remember to like, share, and subscribe for more inspiring stories like this.

resultVideos.Title: Islam and Politics: Crash Course World History 216
resultVideos.Description:
In which John Green teaches you about how Islam has interacted with politics during its history, and how it continues to do so today. Islamist movements are in the news a lot lately, but how did that happen. John will point out that Islam has always been tied to political movements. Mohammed was not only a religious leader, he led an empire. So how did this lead to modern movements like ISIS? Islam has traditionally been a pretty egalitarian religion, and its scriptures value peace, so it is surprising in a lot of ways that such a violent fundamentalist movement would come out of it. What is a caliphate? What is a Caliph? John will teach you all about it. Take it easy in the comments, y'all. Be kind and respectful to each other.

recommandationVideos.Description:
In which John Green teaches you the history of Islam, including the revelation of the Qu'ran to Muhammad, the five pillars of Islam, how the Islamic empire got its start, the Rightly Guided Caliphs, and more. Learn about hadiths, Abu Bakr, and whether the Umma has anything to do with Uma Thurman (spoiler alert: it doesn't). Also, learn a little about the split between Sunni and Shia Muslims, and how to tell if this year's Ramadan is going to be difficult for your Muslim friends. Let's try to keep the flame wars out of this reasoned discussion.

recommandationVideos.Title: History of Israel-Palestine Conflict
recommandationVideos.Description:
This video presents the History of Israel-Palestine conflict that rooted a few thousand years ago. 

Chapter:
00:00 Introduction
00:42 Early History of Israeli-Palestinian conflict
03:11 Israel and Palestine under the British rule
04:25 The Birth of the Israel State
05:12 The 1948 Arab-Israeli War
06:15 The Six-Day War
07:01 The First Intifada and the Oslo Accords
08:38 The Second Intifada
09:21 Israel conflict with Hamas

In the 17 centuries BC, following the call of God, Abraham, Isaac, Jacob settled in Canaan, later known as the Land of Israel. In 1000 BC, King Saul established the Israelite monarchy, which was later split into the Kingdom of Israel and the Kingdom of Judah. The conquest of Roman Empire in 63 BC gave the name ‚ÄúPalestine‚Äù to Judah. During this time, Christianity became a dominant religion towards the end of the Roman Empire. In 636 came an Arab conquest, beginning the spread of Islam. In the 11th century, Christians in Europe launched several crusades to bring the Holy City back to the hand of the Christians while from the 16th century, more and more Jews were joining a movement called Zionism aiming to create a Jewish national state in its ancient homeland.

WWI exploded in 1918 and ended with the collapse of the Ottoman Empire. Its land in the Middle East was carved by the British and French Empires. The region under the control of Britain was what it called the British mandate for Palestine. Tensions between the Jews and the Arabs who both claimed the land grew, which even led to acts of violence.

In 1947, the UN partitioned Palestine into two independent states: a Jewish state and an Arab state with the City of Jerusalem becoming an international zone with a special status. Less than one year after that, Israel declared itself an independent state. Right after the declaration, the 1948 Arab-Israeli War broke out and ended when a cease-fire agreement was reached in 1949, giving more than two-thirds of historic Palestine, including West Jerusalem, to Israel. 

There came more wars and fighting in the following decades, namely the Six-Day War ending with the victory of Israel, the 1982 Israeli invasion of Lebanon kicking the Palestinian Liberation Organization out of Beirut, the First Intifada ending with the Oslo Accords, the Second Intifada ending with Israel‚Äôs withdrawal from Gaza.

Then came the establishment of Hamas, a Sunni Islamist militant group founded in 1987, aiming to destroy the state of Israel and create an Islamic state. After the Battle of Gaza (a conflict between Hamas and Fatah), Hamas split from the Palestinian authority and gained power in the Gaza while the West Bank was separately controlled by the PLO. 

Israel put Gaza under a suffocating blockade, leading to several bloody wars between Israel and Hamas, the military group in control of the Gaza Strip till today.

What caused wars between Israel and Palestine?
Do you think Israel and Palestine can reach a peace treaty?

recommandationVideos.Title: The Mughal Empire and Historical Reputation: Crash Course World History #217
recommandationVideos.Description:
In which John Green teaches you about the Mughal Empire, which ruled large swaths of the Indian Sub-Continent from 1526 to (technically) 1857. While John teaches you about this long-lived Muslim empire, he'll also look at the idea of historical reputation and how we view people from history. Namely, he'll look at the reputations of Mughal emperors Akbar I and Aurangzeb. Traditionally, Akbar I is considered the emperor that made the Mughal Empire great, and Aurangzeb gets the blame for running the whole thing into the ground and setting it up for decline. Is that really how it was, though? It turns out, it's complicated.

recommandationVideos.Title: The rise and fall of the medieval Islamic Empire - Petra Sijpesteijn & Birte Kristiansen
recommandationVideos.Description:
Trace the rise and fall of the Islamic Empire, from the prophet Muhammad in the 7th century to the sacking of Baghdad. 

--

In the 7th century CE, the prophet Muhammad united the people of the Arabian Peninsula through the formation of Islam. Over the next 30 years, caliphs conquered vast areas beyond Arabia, including their mighty neighbors the Persians and Byzantines. But an empire this vast was at risk of conflict and fracture. Petra Sijpesteijn and Birte Kristiansen detail the rise and fall of the Islamic Empire.

Lesson by Petra Sijpesteijn & Birte Kristiansen, directed by Elahe Baloochi, Fardi Mahmoodi.

recommandationVideos.Title: Luther and the Protestant Reformation: Crash Course World History #218
recommandationVideos.Description:
In which John Green teaches you about the Protestant Reformation. Prior to the Protestant Reformation, pretty much everyone in Europe was a Roman Catholic. Not to get all "great man," but Martin Luther changed all that. Martin Luther didn't like the corruption he saw in the church, especially the sale of indulgences, so he left the church and started his own. And it caught on! And it really did kind of change the world. The changes increased literacy and education, and some even say the Protestant Reformation was the beginning of Capitalism in Europe.

recommandationVideos.Title: Iran's Revolutions: Crash Course World History 226
recommandationVideos.Description:
In which John Green teaches you about Iran's Revolutions. Yes, revolutions plural. What was the the1979 Iranian Revolution about? It turns out that Iran has a pretty long history of unrest in order to put power in the hands of the people, and the most recent revolution in 1979 was, at least at first, not necessarily about creating an Islamic state. It certainly turned out to be about that, but it was initially just about people who wanted to get rid of an oppressive regime. Listen up as John teaches you about Iran's long history of revolution.

recommandationVideos.Title: Islam and Politics: Crash Course World History 216
recommandationVideos.Description:
In which John Green teaches you about how Islam has interacted with politics during its history, and how it continues to do so today. Islamist movements are in the news a lot lately, but how did that happen. John will point out that Islam has always been tied to political movements. Mohammed was not only a religious leader, he led an empire. So how did this lead to modern movements like ISIS? Islam has traditionally been a pretty egalitarian religion, and its scriptures value peace, so it is surprising in a lot of ways that such a violent fundamentalist movement would come out of it. What is a caliphate? What is a Caliph? John will teach you all about it. Take it easy in the comments, y'all. Be kind and respectful to each other.

recommandationVideos.Title: Does the Quran Prophesy the End of Israel? | Dr. Shabir Ally
recommandationVideos.Description:
Does the Quran prophesy the end of the state of Israel? There's been a lot of social media commentary on this subject, and Dr. Shabir Ally weighs in. He says that chapter 17 in the Quran is thought to be a commentary on current affairs. He says this modern interpretation comes from a place of desperation and a desire to find hope in the Quran. However, he argues that the verses in question were futuristic from the time God told the Israelites it would happen, but not futuristic in our time. Dr. Shabir doesn't like this modern interpretation for another reason: it likens contemporary Muslims to those who originally destroyed the temple in 586 BC. He says we can draw an indirect lesson from this verse: all human beings need to be aware that if they misuse the power God gives them, God can diminish them in this life.

recommandationVideos.Title: Islam's 'Golden Age' - Rise of the Abbasids
recommandationVideos.Description:
Crusader Kings 3 is free to play on Steam May 11-15, 2023 -  use this link to play now... https://play.crusaderkings.com/EpicHistoryTV

In the 8th century Middle East, a new dynasty seized control of one of the world‚Äôs greatest empires ‚Äì the Islamic Caliphate. Though little remembered in the west today, the Abbasids reigned for five centuries. They oversaw an era of Islamic military dominance... city-building‚Ä¶ brilliant scholarship, and technological innovation. It has come to be remembered as Islam‚Äôs ‚Äògolden age‚Äô. This is the story of the Abbasid Caliphate.

Thank you to our series historical consultant, Professor Antoine Borrut of the University of Maryland. Find out more about his research and publications here: https://history.umd.edu/directory/antoine-borrut

Thank you also to YouTube channel Al Muqaddimah for additional help with research. Watch great history videos on Islamic history at: https://www.youtube.com/@AlMuqaddimahYT
---------------------------------

üìö Some recommended reading provided by Prof. Borrut for those wishing to know about the Abbasids (as an Amazon Associate I earn from qualifying purchases):

üìñ A recent & comprehensive overview of Abbasid Baghdad and Abbasid culture: Emily Selove, Baghdad at the Centre of a World, 8th-13th Century: An Introductory Textbook https://www.amazon.co.uk/Baghdad-Centre-World-8th-13th-Century/dp/1944296158?tag=ephitv0b-21

üìñ The funniest (and excellent) introduction to the topic (comic book): Emily Selove, Popeye and Curly: 120 Days in Medieval Baghdad https://www.amazon.co.uk/Popeye-Curly-Days-Medieval-Baghdad/dp/1944296190/ref=sr_1_1?tag=ephitv0b-21&crid=382P06ICW8JUQ&keywords=Emily Selove, Popeye and Curly&qid=1683105572&s=books&sprefix=emily selove popeye and curly,stripbooks,66&sr=1-1

üìñ The most accessible narrative on the Abbasid dynasty: Hugh Kennedy, When Baghdad Ruled the Muslim World: The Rise and Fall of Islam‚Äôs Greatest Dynasty https://www.amazon.co.uk/When-Baghdad-Ruled-Muslim-World/dp/0306814358/ref=sr_1_1?tag=ephitv0b-21&crid=6AXHGDF4BOJP&keywords=Hugh Kennedy, When Baghdad Ruled the Muslim World&qid=1683105401&s=books&sprefix=hugh kennedy when baghdad ruled the muslim world,stripbooks,71&sr=1-1

 üìñ To move away from the aura of masculinity surrounding the period: Nadia Maria El Cheikh, Women, Islam, and Abbasid Identity https://bookshop.org/a/99532/9780674736368 / https://uk.bookshop.org/a/12275/9780674736368

üìñ An excellent biography of a major Abbasid caliph: Michael Cooperson, Al-Ma‚Äômun https://uk.bookshop.org/a/12275/9781851683864 / https://www.amazon.co.uk/Al-Mamun-Makers-Muslim-Michael-Cooperson/dp/1851683860/ref=sr_1_fkmr0_1?tag=ephitv0b-21&crid=4T91N1E942Z3&keywords=Michael Cooperson, Al-Ma‚Äômun&qid=1683105527&s=books&sprefix=michael cooperson al-ma mun,stripbooks,65&sr=1-1-fkmr0

üìñ Many more excellent biographies in the same series, ‚ÄúMakers of the Muslim World‚Äù: https://www.simonandschuster.com/series/Makers-of-the-Muslim-World

üìñ A thought-provoking discussion of the making of a discrete Muslim identity in pre-Abbasid times: Fred M. Donner, Muhammad and the Believers: At the Origins of Islam https://bookshop.org/a/99532/9780674064140 / https://uk.bookshop.org/a/12275/9780674064140

recommandationVideos.Title: How Russia Lost the First Chechen War - Modern History DOCUMENTARY
recommandationVideos.Description:
Kings and Generals animated historical documentary series on the history of modern warfare continues with a video explaining how Russia lost the First Chechen war.

üé• Join our YouTube members and patrons to unlock exclusive content! Our community is currently enjoying deep dives into the First Punic War, Pacific War, history of Prussia, Italian Unification Wars, Russo-Japanese War, Albigensian Crusade, and Xenophon‚Äôs Anabasis. Become a part of this exclusive circle: youtube.com/channel/UCMmaBzfCCwZ2KqaBJjkj0fw/join or patron: https://www.patreon.com/kingsandgenerals and Paypal http://paypal.me/kingsandgenerals as well!

Embark on a comprehensive journey through the turbulent saga of Chechnya's quest for autonomy in the First Chechen War. Explore the historical evolution of the Chechen people, from their pagan origins to the impact of late medieval Islamization. Delve into the resilient defiance against the Russian Empire's southward expansion, leading to pivotal moments such as the Soviet Union's incorporation of Chechnya and the devastating deportation of the Chechen people in 1944.

Uncover the socio-economic challenges and institutional disparities faced by the Chechen population within the Soviet Union, culminating in the rise of pro-independence sentiment and the election of nationalist leader Dzokhar Dudayev. Witness Chechnya's bold unilateral secession from Russia and the ensuing clashes, marked by the struggle for autonomy against Russian opposition.

Gain insight into the intricacies of the conflict, including Russia's attempts to thwart Chechnya's independence, the phases of military strategies employed, and the significance of key battles like the intense siege and capture of Grozny. Dive deep into the complexities of guerrilla warfare and the evolving tactics that shaped the course of the war.

Experience the ebb and flow of conflict, from strategic gains to devastating losses, as both sides grappled for control. Learn about the impact of various interventions, including Russia's administrative changes, as well as pivotal moments like Dudayev's demise and the rise of Aslan Maskhadov as a new Chechen leader.

Explore the humanitarian toll amidst the chaos, with detailed insights into the civilian and military casualties, including varying estimates from different sources. Witness the eventual ceasefire and the Khasavyurt Accord that marked the Chechen resistance movement's triumph over the Russian army.

This detailed historical account captures the complexity, intensity, and human cost of the First Chechen War, providing an in-depth exploration of a conflict that shaped the destiny of Chechnya.

recommandationVideos.Title: Israel-Hamas at war: Israel 'has lost the moral high ground', says NRC Secretary General Jan Egeland
recommandationVideos.Description:
In the 110 days since the war started, over 25,000 Palestinians have been killed in Israel's offensive on Gaza, prompting the charity Oxfam to describe it as the ‚Äòdeadliest conflict of the 21st century‚Äô. It follows the October 7 attacks by Hamas that saw 1,200 people killed and around 240 taken hostage in Israel. There is huge pressure internationally for a new ceasefire and hostage release deal to alleviate the suffering of Palestinian civilians in Gaza and the remaining Israeli hostages held by Hamas.

(Subscribe: https://bit.ly/C4_News_Subscribe)

In this episode of The Fourcast we speak with Jan Egeland, a former diplomat who helped draw up the 1993 peace agreements between Israel and the Palestine Liberation Organization, the Oslo Accords. 

Egeland, who is now the Secretary General of the Norwegian Refugee Council, tells Krishnan Guru-Murthy that the scale of civilian carnage in Gaza makes it clear that this is not a conflict between equals. He also looks at the ‚Äòhypocritical‚Äô position of many Western governments who have been quick to call out Russia‚Äôs aggression on Ukraine but are not doing the same with Israel‚Äôs attacks on Palestine, and looks at how the conflict could worsen going forward if a two-state solution is not reached.

üìö Some recommended reading provided by Prof. Borrut for those wishing to know about the Abbasids (as an Amazon Associate I earn from qualifying purchases):

üìñ A recent & comprehensive overview of Abbasid Baghdad and Abbasid culture: Emily Selove, Baghdad at the Centre of a World, 8th-13th Century: An Introductory Textbook https://www.amazon.co.uk/Baghdad-Centre-World-8th-13th-Century/dp/1944296158?tag=ephitv0b-21

üìñ The funniest (and excellent) introduction to the topic (comic book): Emily Selove, Popeye and Curly: 120 Days in Medieval Baghdad https://www.amazon.co.uk/Popeye-Curly-Days-Medieval-Baghdad/dp/1944296190/ref=sr_1_1?tag=ephitv0b-21&crid=382P06ICW8JUQ&keywords=Emily Selove, Popeye and Curly&qid=1683105572&s=books&sprefix=emily selove popeye and curly,stripbooks,66&sr=1-1

üìñ The most accessible narrative on the Abbasid dynasty: Hugh Kennedy, When Baghdad Ruled the Muslim World: The Rise and Fall of Islam‚Äôs Greatest Dynasty https://www.amazon.co.uk/When-Baghdad-Ruled-Muslim-World/dp/0306814358/ref=sr_1_1?tag=ephitv0b-21&crid=6AXHGDF4BOJP&keywords=Hugh Kennedy, When Baghdad Ruled the Muslim World&qid=1683105401&s=books&sprefix=hugh kennedy when baghdad ruled the muslim world,stripbooks,71&sr=1-1

 üìñ To move away from the aura of masculinity surrounding the period: Nadia Maria El Cheikh, Women, Islam, and Abbasid Identity https://bookshop.org/a/99532/9780674736368 / https://uk.bookshop.org/a/12275/9780674736368

üìñ An excellent biography of a major Abbasid caliph: Michael Cooperson, Al-Ma‚Äômun https://uk.bookshop.org/a/12275/9781851683864 / https://www.amazon.co.uk/Al-Mamun-Makers-Muslim-Michael-Cooperson/dp/1851683860/ref=sr_1_fkmr0_1?tag=ephitv0b-21&crid=4T91N1E942Z3&keywords=Michael Cooperson, Al-Ma‚Äômun&qid=1683105527&s=books&sprefix=michael cooperson al-ma mun,stripbooks,65&sr=1-1-fkmr0

üìñ Many more excellent biographies in the same series, ‚ÄúMakers of the Muslim World‚Äù: https://www.simonandschuster.com/series/Makers-of-the-Muslim-World

üìñ A thought-provoking discussion of the making of a discrete Muslim identity in pre-Abbasid times: Fred M. Donner, Muhammad and the Believers: At the Origins of Islam https://bookshop.org/a/99532/9780674064140 / https://uk.bookshop.org/a/12275/9780674064140
